		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_64673768" name="comment_link_64673768" href="//linux.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23408192&amp;cid=64673768" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64673768)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64673768" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64673768); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~williamyf">williamyf</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~williamyf">( 227051 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64673768"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64673768"><p><div class="quote"><p>Windows has a malware scanner and stomper built into the OS.  Linux doesn't.  Is this something that will hamstring Linux on the desktop in the future?</p></div><p>There was a time when windows did not have a MS provided antivirus (for fear of antitrust action). That was from Win1.0 all the way until Vista.<br>All the antiviruses you would get were 3rd parties, bundled in by the OEM. Even when MS bundled an AV (with MO-DOS) it was a 3rd party licensed product (PC-Tool IIRC).</p><p>There is a free antivirus for Linux, called ClamAV. Many distros incorporate it by default.</p><p>So no, lack of antivirus is not hindering "the year of the linux desktop". Rather, probably is lack of apps th<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64673768">

